Here's how to wire everything up:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service — Singleton
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — Transient
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — Transient
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps an `HttpClient` / REST connection. One instance avoids socket exhaustion and lets you share auth tokens, caching, or retry policies app-wide. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation creates a fresh VM with clean state—no stale data leaking between visits. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Matches the ViewModel lifetime so each page gets its own VM. Avoids UI state bugs on re-navigation. |

**Key rules of thumb:**

- **Singleton** — stateless or intentionally shared (HTTP clients, caches, config).
- **Transient** — stateful per-interaction (ViewModels, pages).
- **Scoped** — rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET), but useful if you create manual scopes for workflows.

> ⚠️ Never inject a Transient or Scoped service into a Singleton—it effectively becomes a singleton too (captured dependency problem).
